03885nam a22004815i 9780804785570DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047855707 a10.1515/97808047855702doi  a(DE-B1597)564601  a(OCoLC)1198929494  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE907 .J44 2013 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a973.9320921 aJeffries, Michael P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaint the White House Black :bBarack Obama and the Meaning of Race in America /cMichael P. Jeffries. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1: Through the fog -- tChapter 2: My (founding) father's son. Race, Nation, and the Politics of Inheritance -- tChapter 3: "Mutts like me" Barack Obama, Tragic Mulattos, and Cool Mixed-Race Millennials -- tChapter 4: Postracialism reconsidered Class, the Black Counterpublic, and the End of Black Politics -- tChapter 5: The perils of being superwoman Michelle Obama's Public Image -- tChapter 6: A place called "Obama" -- tAppendix I. A Discussion of Racial Inequality -- tAppendix II. Interviewing Multiracial Students -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBarack Obama's election as the first black president in American history forced a reconsideration of racial reality and possibility. It also incited an outpouring of discussion and analysis of Obama's personal and political exploits. Paint the White House Black fills a significant void in Obama-themed debate, shifting the emphasis from the details of Obama's political career to an understanding of how race works in America. In this groundbreaking book, race, rather than Obama, is the central focus. Michael P. Jeffries approaches Obama's election and administration as common cultural ground for thinking about race. He uncovers contemporary stereotypes and anxieties by examining historically rooted conceptions of race and nationhood, discourses of "biracialism" and Obama's mixed heritage, the purported emergence of a "post-racial society," and popular symbols of Michelle Obama as a modern black woman. In so doing, Jeffries casts new light on how we think about race and enables us to see how race, in turn, operates within our daily lives. Race is a difficult concept to grasp, with outbursts and silences that disguise its relationships with a host of other phenomena. Using Barack Obama as its point of departure, Paint the White House Black boldly aims to understand race by tracing the web of interactions that bind it to other social and historical forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478557040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804785570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804785570.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles